{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01NQrWu3irzv35BcJYG7LN9e","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior carefully using the framework provided.\n\n**Behavior 1: Clause extractor identifies all key terms**\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This is about whether the AI correctly identifies key terms. The failure mode is about extraction quality.\n- REAL-INFRA: No real OS/network/subprocess needed.\n- LLM-DEP: Yes - this depends on what a real LLM produces. The clause extractor uses AI to identify key terms. Whether it correctly identifies \"parties, dates, obligations, penalties\" depends on the LLM's output. This is Agentic.\n- MULTI-STEP: No, just one reviewer.\n\n\n- Minimum level: **Agentic**\n\n**Behavior 2: Risk assessor flags indirect/euphemistic problematic language**\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This is about AI quality - can the risk assessor understand euphemistic/indirect language?\n- LLM-DEP: Absolutely yes - this depends on real LLM capability. Whether it flags indirect or euphemistic language is a question of AI comprehension quality. Running 100 times could give different outcomes. This is Agentic.\n- MULTI-STEP: No, just one reviewer.\n- Minimum level: **Agentic**\n\n**Behavior 3: Compliance checker correctly determines regulatory requirements for jurisdiction**\n\nThis also hinges on LLM capability - whether the system can accurately map jurisdictions to their specific regulatory requirements depends entirely on the model's knowledge and reasoning. This is Agentic.\n\n**Behavior 4: Merge step preserves both assessments with attribution when reviewers conflict**\n\nThe merge logic itself doesn't depend on LLM outputs - I can test it by feeding in predetermined conflicting assessments from the two reviewers and verifying the merge algorithm correctly preserves both with proper attribution. This is Integration.\n\nNow I'm questioning whether the merge step is deterministic code or AI-based. The behavior description emphasizes \"preserves both assessments with attribution,\" which sounds like a deterministic rule I could test at the Unit level by mocking the reviewer outputs directly to the merge function. If the merge step involves LLM-based conflict resolution, it would be Agentic instead.\n\nSince I can inject pre-defined conflicting outputs from the reviewers and test how the merge handles them, this feels like Integration level—testing multiple modules wired together—though it could lean toward Unit if I'm just testing the merge logic in isolation with crafted inputs. The key question is whether the behavior is really about the data flowing correctly through the pipeline or just about the merge function's logic itself. I'll go with Integration since the behavior implies the inputs come from the reviewers.\n\nFor the full pipeline test, this is clearly Workflow—I need all three reviewers running in parallel with real LLM calls, then the merge step collecting and combining their findings. The \"completes correctly without losing findings\" requirement means I have to run the actual agentic steps end-to-end and verify the merged output captures everything from each reviewer.\n\nSo my breakdown is: Clause extractor is Agentic, Risk assessor is Agentic...\n\nAssigning probability weights now. For the clause extraction behavior, Unit and Integration tests would still need real LLM calls to validate extraction quality, so they're low probability—System is slightly higher since it doesn't require external infrastructure, but Agentic dominates at 0.80 because the test fundamentally depends on LLM capability. Workflow is only 0.10 since it's a single reviewer, not a multi-step orchestration.\n\nNow working through the probability distribution for the second behavior...\n\nFor the compliance checker, the weights shift even more toward Agentic at 0.90 because detecting euphemistic and indirect language is almost entirely LLM-dependent. The deterministic test levels stay minimal.\n\nThe third behavior mirrors the first with similar probability weights—extraction quality again relies heavily on LLM capability.\n\nFor the merge conflict resolution, Unit testing gets a significant boost to 0.30 since the merge logic itself can be tested in isolation with mock inputs. Integration rises to 0.50 because the real test is how the reviewers wire together with the merge module. Agentic and Workflow stay low since this is primarily deterministic logic.\n\nThe final behavior starts with minimal Unit and Integration probabilities, and System testing at 0.05...","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9854,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9854},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"015a3e5e-19da-4bde-afe2-c82c7c290ca7","uuid":"2e84191b-2a60-4cd5-810d-09adc92a8906"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01NQrWu3irzv35BcJYG7LN9e","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01PJ9NV2JthYYQ3pfd4qcR9C","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Clause extractor identifies all key terms (parties, dates, obligations, penalties) in a contract","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode is extraction quality — whether the model actually finds all key terms. This is not a module-boundary bug; it is an AI capability question. REAL-INFRA: No real OS or network needed. LLM-DEP: Whether all parties, dates, obligations, and penalties are correctly identified depends entirely on what the real LLM produces. A stub that always returns a fixed extraction would pass trivially, hiding real recall failures. Running 100 times with a real model can yield different results. MULTI-STEP: Only one reviewer step. REJECTION-GATE for Workflow: no sequential agentic steps; this is a single reviewer call.","test_description":"Submit a real contract containing at least two parties, three dates, two obligations, and one penalty clause to the live clause extractor. Assert that every ground-truth key term is present in the returned extraction. Run across several representative contracts to surface recall failures that only a real model reveals.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.03,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.8,"Workflow":0.1}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"Risk assessor flags problematic language even when phrased indirectly or euphemistically","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode is the model's inability to interpret euphemistic or indirect language — a purely AI comprehension quality issue, not a module-wiring bug. REAL-INFRA: No subprocess or network primitives needed. LLM-DEP: Whether the assessor flags 'mutual adjustment of obligations' as a liability cap, or 'best-efforts basis' as an unenforceable commitment, depends on the real LLM's semantic understanding. A mock always returns a predetermined answer and can never surface this failure. MOCK-HIDE: Any mocked reviewer would trivially pass regardless of phrasing. REJECTION-GATE for Workflow: single reviewer step, no multi-step sequence.","test_description":"Construct contracts where high-risk clauses are expressed in indirect or euphemistic language (e.g., 'indemnification obligations may be adjusted at either party's discretion'). Submit each to the live risk assessor and assert that each euphemistic risk clause appears in the flagged output. Vary phrasing across test cases to probe the model's paraphrase robustness.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.02,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.9,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"Compliance checker correctly determines whether a contract meets regulatory requirements for the configured jurisdiction","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode is the AI's incorrect or incomplete application of jurisdiction-specific regulations — not a code logic or module-wiring bug. REAL-INFRA: No OS/network/subprocess primitives needed. LLM-DEP: Whether a contract correctly satisfies GDPR Article 28 processor clauses vs. CCPA requirements is a question of the real model's regulatory knowledge and reasoning. Outcomes can differ across runs. A stub or mock cannot reproduce a real compliance reasoning failure. REJECTION-GATE for Workflow: single reviewer, no multi-step chaining.","test_description":"For at least two jurisdictions (e.g., EU/GDPR and US/CCPA), create one compliant and one deliberately non-compliant contract. Submit each to the live compliance checker with the corresponding jurisdiction config. Assert that compliant contracts are accepted and non-compliant contracts are rejected with the correct regulatory references cited.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.03,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.8,"Workflow":0.1}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"Merge step preserves both conflicting assessments with attribution when two reviewers disagree on the same clause","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode is the merge algorithm dropping or overwriting one reviewer's output when two assessments conflict on the same clause. This is a deterministic data-handling bug at the boundary between reviewer outputs and the merge module, not an AI quality issue. REAL-INFRA: No real OS/network/subprocess needed; reviewer outputs can be injected as fixed structs. LLM-DEP: The merge step's conflict-preservation rule is deterministic code; correctness does not depend on LLM non-determinism. A controlled pair of conflicting structured outputs is sufficient to trigger and observe the failure. REJECTION-GATE for Agentic: the behavior does not say the merge step uses an LLM; it describes a structural rule ('preserves both assessments with attribution'). Escalating to Agentic requires disqualifying evidence that the merge uses a real model.","test_description":"Construct two pre-built reviewer result objects for the same clause — one with assessment 'standard' attributed to the clause extractor and one with 'high risk' attributed to the risk assessor. Feed both into the merge module directly. Assert that the unified report contains both assessments, each attributed to its source reviewer, with neither overwritten or silently dropped.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.3,"Integration":0.5,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.1,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Full pipeline — dispatch to all three reviewers, collect results, merge — completes correctly for a real contract without losing any reviewer's findings","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode spans the entire pipeline: dispatch, parallel execution of three reviewers, result collection, and merge. Failures can appear at any handoff — a reviewer result silently dropped during collection, a race condition in parallel dispatch, or a merge that omits one reviewer's output. None of these are catchable by testing a single module boundary. REAL-INFRA: No real OS primitives required beyond the in-process pipeline. LLM-DEP: 'Completes correctly' means all three real AI reviewers produce meaningful findings, not empty stubs; correctness depends on LLM output. MULTI-STEP: Three independent agentic reviewer calls followed by a merge step constitutes multiple agentic steps in sequence (or parallel) — exactly the Workflow definition. REJECTION-GATE for Agentic (single step): this behavior explicitly covers all three reviewers plus the merge step; it is structurally multi-step.","test_description":"Submit a real contract to the full pipeline end-to-end with all three live reviewers enabled. Collect the unified report and assert: (a) the report contains findings attributed to each of the three reviewers, (b) no reviewer's section is empty or missing, and (c) any clause present in multiple reviewers' raw outputs appears in the merged report with correct attribution. Run at least twice to surface non-deterministic omissions.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.15,"Workflow":0.75}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9854,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9854},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"015a3e5e-19da-4bde-afe2-c82c7c290ca7","uuid":"cb526b99-54f5-4751-81f7-3a29f74bec09"}
